hem as fragile mountain ecosystems to be protected from global forces of destruction. Places in Knots shows how these tropes of remoteness inform development and conservation policies and thus shape the contexts in which Himalayan connections with the wider world are forged and maintained. Following Himalayan journeys between valleys in Nepal and beyond, Saxer draws a picture of globalization that emerges not from the centers or below-but rather from the edge. Thanks to generous funding from LMU München, the ebook editions of this book are available as Open Access volumes from Cornell Open (cornellpress.cornell.edu/cornell-open) and other repositories.  afunded by LMU München  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aAsian Studies. 4aGEOGRAPHY. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  amobile himalayan communities, nepal new york connections, road construction in nepal, himalayan trade, villages in walung and upper humla, cross-border relationships between tibet and nepal.2 aLMU Münchenefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501766879?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501766879zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501766879/original  a978-3-11-075183-3 Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA